It's impossible to map numbers to a double datatype using match_mapping_type. Although clarification is still necessary, it's important to clarify how to do this. The JSON parser assumes a wider datatype other than a BigDecimal/BigInteger. This way, floating-point numbers will be detected as a double instead of a float, and integers will be detected as a long instead of an integer. You can dynamically map floating-point numbers to doubles by using double as a match_mapping_type and double as a type i.

I'm having the same issue. On Windows 10, there is a feature called UI Scaling described in this article. It's a useful feature for visually impaired users to make the text and GUI elements larger in most Windows programs. However, when enabled, two very bad things can happen to libGDX: 1. In full-screen mode, we only see the upper left portion of the viewport zoomed in according to the degree of UI scaling. 2. The Nearest Neighbor pixel rendering gets messy and displays blurry pixels.

Most graphics subsystems have a maximum output of around 30k pixels in either direction, so anytime you approach that, you're more likely to encounter problems. Are you actually below 30k pixels in either dimension? In other circumstances, like a hidden display or resizing, the limit can be even higher, reaching around 15k pixels. This is an unconventional operating system limitation that we obviously cannot control. However, if we can figure out where it's failing, we might include an error message or a warning about it.
